Beneath the slotted, gothic visor of his ancient terminator armor, the Demagogue's face was detached and impassive as he watched the last thrashings of the Imperial cardinal as he finally drowned.  Irony was one of the last justices the chaos lord could find, and so one could say he enjoyed holding the priest under in his own baptism pool, which he had filled with the blood of the priest's acolytes, just for that extra touch.  He did this at every temple he ransacked, and it had earned him his name - but it was getting old.  This time was a bit different, however - the priest still clutched his scattergun.  Beh'ri had allowed him to keep it, but the old man had forgotten it in his panic.  This was good...ironic, even.  A faint smile tugged at the Dark Apostle's lips.<br>
<br>
The moment was ruined as someone cleared their throat behind him.  Beh'ri felt his face snap into its more customary grim placidness, threw the priest to splatter wetly across the Imperial icon set onto the pulpit, and turned to face the intruder.  Heavy robes and cowl, green armor, and the pistols identified the Fallen One.<br>
<br>
"So the portents and visions speak true, Cypher.  You act as Abbadon's lapdog in this?"<br>
<br>
If the other took offense, he gave no sign.  "I act as his messenger this day, your Unholiness.  You are to awaken your rival in the deep, then preach your words of revolt and destruction across the sectors outlying the Eye, especially Cadia.  You are also the key to the Sylph Gates, which he would see open.  The Warmaster said you would understand these instructions."<br>
<br>
Beh'ri paused in thought for a moment, then began stomping towards the doors of the temple as his booming voice issued from his aeons-old helm, "I do.  And so shall his favor be returned in full.  For the glory of the Pantheon I go, all praises unto Their names."<br>
<br>
Cypher was already gone.<br>
<br>
*********************************<br>
<br>
A storm lashed the seas surrounding the crest of Hive Secundus, barely poking up out of the planet-wide ocean of Durst's Reach.  The sailor's tarp thrown over his bulky armor as he had been smuggled in was ripped away by a screaming wind, revealing the Popeinator in all his dark glory.  Brandishing both his Accursed Crozarius and an odd pyramidal ornament on a chain of matching sea gold, Beh'ri shouted horrendous words, the amplifiers of his terminator suit carrying the chant all the way through the bulkheads of the hive, leaving the nobles within to cower, scream, and jab hairpins in their ears to stop the awful pain they brought.<br>
<br>
"Ia, Cthulhu fthagn!  Ia, Hydra, Ia, Dagon!  Ia, Cthulhu fthagn!  Ia, Tentaculon, fthagn!  Ia, Tentaculon, Ia!  Ia!  Ia!"<br>
<br>
The storm somehow worsened as the sea began to bubble as if boiling.  Finally, a massive stone bier burst forth from the sea to float under its own power, bearing its awful cargo and master.  Countless reptilian heads all sounded their displeasure at once, killing the Secundus nobility that still possessed eardrums with their hatred.<br>
<br>
The Dark Apostle looked across the black waves at his rival, staring unflinchingly at the waving serpents.  Beh'ri held his silence until he finally chose a larger head near the center of the squirming mass to address.  "Enough, Old One.  There is no place for our games in the immediate times to come.  The Despoiler has called in our mutual debt.  We are to combine our forces and our efforts, and topple the systems that dare guard the Eye.  I am to open the Gates of our ancestors, and we shall strike at every heart that beats within the chest of the False Emperor's crumbling work.  Call your children to break down the walls of this hive, for mine await us in ships at its dock.  We shall travel where needed, bringing with us the glory of Chaos Undivided!"<br>
<br>
The man-turned-beast in armor bearing Alpha Legion markings screamed his understanding before sinking back below the churning, inky darkness to summon its servants.  The beast-in-the-form-of-man wearing the heraldry of a Word Bearers Chaplain turned back to the center of the hive crest, where he had burned a hole in the hull protecting the orbital elevator.<br>
<br>
